'''Colossae''' ({{IPAc-en|k|ə|ˈ|l|ɒ|s|i}}; [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: [[wikt:Κολοσσαί|Κολοσσαί]]) was an ancient city of [[Phrygia]] in Asia Minor, and was the location to which the [[Paul the Apostle|Apostle Paul]] directed his [[Epistle to the Colossians]].  A significant city from the 5th Century BC onwards, it had dwindled in importance by the time of Paul, but was notable for the existence of its local angel cult.  It was part of the Roman – and then Byzantine – province of [[Phrygia Pacatiana]], before being destroyed in 1192/3 and its population relocating to nearby Chonae (modern day [[Honaz]]).

==Origin and etymology of place name==
{{empty section|date=February 2016}}

==Location and geography==
Colossae was located in [[Phrygia]], in Asia Minor.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S5GJaakRvPgC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71&dq=Colossae+was+located+in+Phrygia,+in+Asia+Minor.&source=bl&ots=qYdJwFpvyO&sig=i7_PSwRcnV-oZvCqDa-xvFBzRyg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjL4ZukgbvRAhWHWCYKHXt5AEI4ChDoAQgvMAU#v=onepage&q=Colossae%20was%20located%20in%20Phrygia,%20in%20Asia%20Minor.&f=false|title=The Uttermost Part of the Earth: A Guide to Places in the Bible|last=Losch|first=Richard R.|date=2005-01-01|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=9780802828057|language=en}}</ref> It was located 15&nbsp;km southeast of [[Laodicea on the Lycus|Laodicea]] on the road through the [[Lycus (river of Phrygia)|Lycus]] Valley between Sardeis and Celaenae.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/54952013|title=Brill's New Pauly : encyclopaedia of the ancient world. Antiquity. [CAT-CYP]|last=|first=|date=2002-2010|publisher=Brill|others=Cancik, Hubert., Schneider, Helmuth., Salazar, Christine F., Orton, David E.|year=|isbn=9004122664|location=Leiden|pages=579|oclc=54952013}}</ref>  At Colossae, [[Herodotus]] describes how, "the river Lycos falls into an opening of the earth and disappears from view, and then after an interval of about five furlongs it comes up to view again, and this river also flows into the [[Büyük Menderes River|Maiander.]]"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/2456|title=The History of Herodotus — Volume 2 by Herodotus|language=en-US}}</ref>  Despite a treacherously ambiguous cartography and history, Colossae has been clearly distinguished in modern research from nearby ''Chonae'' (Χῶναι), now called [[Honaz]], with what remains of the buried ruins of Colossae ("the mound")  lying 3&nbsp;km to the north of Honaz.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Cadwallader, Alan H.  |author2=Trainor, Michael | year = 2011 | title = Colossae in Space and Time: Linking to an Ancient City | chapter = Colossae in Space and Time: Overcoming Dislocation, Dismemberment and Anachronicity | series = Novum Testamentum et Orbis Antiquus/Studien zur Umwelt des Neuen Testaments (NTOA/StUNT), Vol. 94 | editors = Cadwallader, Alan H. & Trainor, Michael | pages = 9–47 | location = Göttingen, GER | publisher = Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht | isbn = 3647533971 | url = https://books.google.com/books?isbn=3525533977 | access-date = 17 February 2016 | quote = }} The case is made exhaustively in this book, over pages 11-37, wherein it states—after dispensing with a further false association of the ancient city with the island of Rhodes  the home of The Colossus of Rhodes, which resulted in its being misplaced for hundreds of years (by "almost 200 kilometers to the south-west," p. 18ff)—in summary, that: "Colossae's various positions on early maps confirmed the confusion over identity [opening section title]. Cartographers positioned Colossae to the west (rather than south-east) of Laodicea<sup>7</sup> or, as 'Conos', between Laodicea to the north-west and Hieropolis to the north-east.<sup>8</sup> [p. 11] … 'Chonos' or some other guesttimation of the spelling of Honaz<sup>12</sup> sometimes subsumed Colossae. [p. 13] … The inhabitants of the immediate vicinity of the ancient site [Colossae, which had ceased to exist] were shackled in bureaucratic tabulation for tax purposes to the town of Honaz. [p. 14] … When Frances Arundell's sketch of Honaz appeared in 1834, the town had descended from the mountain heights [it was a mountain fortress, Honazdağ] but it was similarly labelled, albeit after the fashion of Nicetas Choniates: 'Chonas, … anciently Colossae'.<sup>98</sup> [p. 32] … The question was whether Honaz and Colossae were to be equated or separated and whether the contemporary Honaz was the means to pinpoint the ancient… site. [p. 33] … William Hamilton became the one credited with the separation of Colossae from Chonai with the former's location at the mound three kilometers to the north of Honaz.<sup>108</sup> [p. 35] … Two photographs of the 'Ruines de Colossae' and 'Chonas' by Henri Carmignac published toward the endif the nineteenth century finally eliminated the concordant visualisation of the places that had been the legacy of Arundell ''(Fig. 11)''.<sup>113</sup> [p. 37]." For much earlier sources presenting the errant historical opinion, see the next two citations.</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = Smith, William | year = 1854 | title = Dictionary of Greek and Roman Geography | chapter = Colossae |  url = http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0064:id=colossae-geo | location =  | publisher =  | access-date =  | quote =  }}{{full citation needed|date=February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = Pétridès, Sophrone  | year = 1908 | title = Catholic Encyclopedia | chapter = Colossae | location = New York, NY | publisher =  | url = http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04131a.htm  | access-date =  | quote =  }}{{full citation needed|date=February 2016}}</ref>

==History==
===Before the Pauline period===

{{expand section | a cohesive account of the history of the municipality and its peoples and cultures, as appear in many texts on the subject | small = no |date=February 2016}}

Writing in the 5th Century BC, [[Xenophon]] refers to Colossae as "a populous city, wealthy and of considerable magnitude".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/22003|title=The First Four Books of Xenophon's Anabasis|last=Watson|first=J. S.|publisher=Project Gutenberg|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=6}}</ref>  It was famous for its wool trade.  [[Strabo]] notes that the city drew great revenue from the flocks, and that the wool of Colossae gave its name to colour ''colossinus''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/44885|title=The Geography of Strabo, Volume 2 (of 3) by Strabo|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=334|language=en-US}}</ref>   In 396 BC, Colossae was the site of the execution of the rebellious Persian satrap [[Tissaphernes]] who was lured there and slain by an agent of the party of [[Cyrus the Younger]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Tissaphernes|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Tissaphernes|journal=1911 Encyclopædia Britannica|volume= 26}}</ref>  Although during the [[Hellenistic]] period, the town was of some mercantile importance, by the 1st century it had dwindled greatly in size and significance.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pAwqB33cr_wC&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Colossae+first+century&source=bl&ots=m_8EbgOhQ7&sig=z8PV_iBFxi_69TlgsSM8U4XtlyY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim_rmQpdvRAhXFZCYKHVKlBusQ6AEIPzAG#v=onepage&q=Colossae%20first%20century&f=false|title=Colossae in Space and Time: Linking to an Ancient City|last=Cadwallader|first=Alan H.|last2=Trainor|first2=Michael|date=2011-12-07|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|isbn=9783647533971|language=en}}</ref>   [[Paul the Apostle|Paul']]<nowiki/>s letter to the Colossians point to the existence of an early Christian community.  The town was known for its fusion of religious influences (syncretism), which included [[ancient Judaism|Jewish]], [[Gnosticism|Gnostic]], and pagan influences that in the first century AD were described as an angel-cult.<ref name="BruceNTH69">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2RyJAAAAMAAJ|title=New Testament History|author=Bruce, F.F. [Frederick Fyvie]|publisher=Galilee/Doubleday|year=1980|isbn=0385025335|location=New York, NY|pages=415f|quote=[Quoting:] Those churches which claimed an apostolic foundation attached great importance to the maintenance of the teaching which they had originally received. There were powerful forces at work in many of them which militated against the maintenance of that teaching; chief among these were those tendencies which in a few decades blossomed forth in the elaborate systems of the various schools of Gnosticism. One form of incipient Gnosticism is the syncretistic angel-cult of nonconformist Jewish foundation and pagan superstructure attacked in the Epistle to the Colossians.|access-date=17 February 2016|orig-year=1969}} A further, less stable online source with access to these pages is available at [https://www.amazon.com/New-Testament-History-F-Bruce/dp/0385025335], accessed same date.</ref>   This unorthodox cult venerated the [[Michael (archangel)|archangel Michael]] who is said to have caused a curative spring to gush from a fissure in the Earth.<ref name=":0" />

===Pauline period===

Colossae was the location of a Christian community to which the [[St. Paul|Apostle Paul]] addressed a [[Colossians|canonically accepted epistle]] (letter),{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} which is known for its content's exaltation of the supremacy of Christianity's namesake.{{citation needed|reason=Col 2:8-10|date=March 2016}} One aim of the letter was to address the challenges that the community faced in its context of the syncretistic Gnostic religions that were developing in Asia minor.<ref name = BruceNTH69/>

Judging from the Letter to the Colossians, [[Epaphras]] was a person of some importance in the Christian community there ({{bibleverse||Col.|1:7|KJV}}; {{bibleverse-nb||Col.|4:12|KJV}}), and tradition presents him as its first bishop.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} It does not appear from his [[Epistle to the Colossians]] that [[Paul of Tarsus|St. Paul]] had visited the city, for the epistle only speaks of him having heard of their faith ({{bibleverse||Col.|1:4|ESV}}) and since he tells [[Philemon of Colossae|Philemon]] of his hope to visit it upon being freed from prison (see [[Philemon 1:22]]). Tradition also gives Philemon as the second bishop of the see.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

The first historically documented bishop is Epiphanius,{{when|date=February 2016}} who was not personally at the [[Council of Chalcedon]], but whose metropolitan bishop Nunechius of [[Laodicea on the Lycus|Laodicea]], the capital of the [[Roman province]] of [[Phrygia Pacatiana]] signed the acts on his behalf.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

===Decimation and destruction===
{{expand section | with SOURCED material relevant to the earthquake and its destruction by the Saracens and the Turks | small = no|date=February 2016}}
The city was decimated by an earthquake in the 60s AD, and was rebuilt independent of the support of Rome.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} The city was later overrun by the [[Saracens]] in the 7th and 8th centuries AD.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

Colossae's famous church was destroyed in 1192/3 during the Byzantine civil wars.  It was a suffragan diocese of Laodicea in Phyrigia Pacatiane but was replaced in the Byzantine period by the Chonae settlement on higher ground<ref name=":0" />

===Modern legacy and study===
{{expand section | with SOURCED material relevant to the history of its mapping and historical and literary discussion (see further reading), and on plans for its excavation | small = no|date=February 2016}}
As of 2015, it had never been excavated,{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} though plans are reported for an Australian led expedition to the site.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

